  "output": "## Performance Analysis — jobsquare\n\nThis is a Python async CLI (no React/frontend, confirmed — `find` turned up zero `.jsx`/`.tsx` files), so I mapped your categories to their real equivalents: SQLite N+1 in `store.py`, redundant per-item computation in `filters.py`, HTTP/DB caching opportunities, and memory bloat instead of \"leaks\" (the process is short-lived). `sources.yaml` configures 132 ATS sources, several with `max_pages` up to 40 pages × 10–20 jobs, so a full run can easily produce several thousand `Job` objects — the issues below scale with that.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\nFor every job fetched this run, `diff()` issues a separate `SELECT` round-trip, then a separate `INSERT`/`UPDATE`:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job)\n        self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    ...\n```\n\nWith thousands of jobs per run, that's thousands of individual `SELECT` statements (plus thousands of `INSERT`/`UPDATE`s) instead of a handful of batched round-trips. SQLite is in-process so it's not network-bound, but it's still ~2N statement executions plus Python-level dict/`asdict()` overhead per job, and it will get materially worse as `jobs.db` grows and the `key` lookup does more B-tree work per call under load from concurrent pipeline workers (per your existing `[[jobsquare-parallel-worker-collisions]]` note).\n\n**Fix — batch the read, single-flight the writes:**\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing: dict[str, str] = {}\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):  # stay under SQLite's default 999-var limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        placeholders = \",\".join(\"?\" * len(chunk))\n        rows = cur.execute(\n            f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({placeholders})\", chunk\n        ).fetchall()\n        existing.update((r[\"key\"], r[\"content_hash\"]) for r in rows)\n\n    new, changed, seen_update = [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        prev_hash = existing.get(job.key)\n        if prev_hash is None:\n            new.append(job)\n        elif prev_hash != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job)\n        else:\n            seen_update.append((now, job.key))\n\n    if new:\n        cur.executemany(\n            \"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (key, source, company, external_id, title, url,\n                 location, department, employment_type, posted_at, salary_range,\n                 content_hash, first_seen, last_seen)\n               VALUES (:key,:source,:company,:external_id,:title,:url,:location,\n                 :department,:employment_type,:posted_at,:salary_range,\n                 :content_hash,:now,:now)\"\"\",\n            [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in new],\n        )\n    if changed:\n        cur.executemany(\n            \"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET title=:title, url=:url, location=:location,\n                 department=:department, employment_type=:employment_type,\n                 posted_at=:posted_at, salary_range=:salary_range,\n                 content_hash=:content_hash, last_seen=:now\n               WHERE key=:key\"\"\",\n            [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in changed],\n        )\n    if seen_update:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", seen_update)\n\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns ~2N statements into O(N/900) reads + 3 batched `executemany` calls.\n\n### 2. Redundant computation — `filters.py:11-41` (regex recompiled per job)\n\n`filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per job, and `match()` calls `_compile(exclude)` / `_compile(include)` **inside itself** every time:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=rules.get(\"include_keywords\"), exclude=rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\"), ...) for j in jobs]\n```\n\n`match()` → `_compile(exclude)` and `_compile(include)` recompile the same keyword list into fresh `re.Pattern` objects **for every single job**. With, say, 10 keywords and 3,000 fetched jobs, that's 30,000+ wasted `re.compile()` calls per run for patterns that never change within the call.\n\n**Fix — compile once, pass down:**\n\n```python\ndef match(job: Job, *, include: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          exclude: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          locations: list[str] | None = None,\n          cutoff: datetime | None = None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = None\n    max_age = rules.get(\"max_age_days\")\n    if max_age:\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = rules.get(\"locations\")\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\nThis is the single highest-value, lowest-risk fix here — pure win, no behavior change.\n\n### 3. Redundant computation — `models.py:66-75` (`content_hash` computed twice per row)\n\n`content_hash` is a `@property` that runs `hashlib.sha256` fresh on every access. In `store.diff()` (current code) it's read once to compare (`row[\"content_hash\"] != job.content_hash`) and then `to_row()` computes it again internally for the `INSERT`/`UPDATE` params. Cheap per-call, but doubled for no reason across every new/changed job.\n\n**Fix:** compute once and pass it through, or cache it on the dataclass:\n\n```python\n@dataclass(slots=True)\nclass Job:\n    ...\n    _content_hash_cache: str | None = field(default=None, repr=False, compare=False)\n\n    @property\n    def content_hash(self) -> str:\n        if self._content_hash_cache is None:\n            blob = \"|\".join((self.title, self.location, self.url, self.department))\n            self._content_hash_cache = hashlib.sha256(blob.encode()).hexdigest()[:16]\n        return self._content_hash_cache\n```\n(Minor — only worth doing if you're already touching `store.diff`; not worth a standalone change.)\n\n### 4. Caching opportunity — no conditional HTTP requests across runs (`fetchers.py`)\n\nThe tool re-fetches every page of every one of 132 sources on every run (agent.py's docstring implies scheduled runs — `12h scheduled run` per recent commit `6ae8083`), including boards with `max_pages: 40` (Microsoft, Amazon) that haven't changed since the last run. Several of these APIs support `ETag`/`If-Modified-Since` or at minimum first-page short-circuiting.\n\nCheapest high-leverage win: for paginated sources you already sort newest-first (Amazon, Microsoft, Netflix, Apple, Google), stash the newest `external_id` seen last run in the `meta` table (same pattern as `last_scan`) and stop paginating as soon as you hit it again, instead of always paginating to `max_pages` or first-empty-page:\n\n```python\n# fetch_amazon, illustrative\nlast_seen_id = source.get(\"_last_top_id\")  # threaded in from meta table\nfor pg in range(max_pages):\n    ...\n    fresh = [j for j in parse_amazon(company, jobs_raw) if j.external_id not in seen]\n    if not fresh:\n        break\n    if last_seen_id and any(j.external_id == last_seen_id for j in fresh):\n        jobs.extend(itertools_takewhile_before(fresh, last_seen_id))\n        break\n    ...\n```\nThis turns \"always fetch up to 400 rows across 40 pages\" into \"usually fetch 1 page\" for boards that barely change between 12h runs — a real bandwidth/latency win, not just CPU.\n\n### 5. Memory bloat (not a leak, but worth trimming) — `fetchers.py` raw payload retention\n\nSeveral parsers (`parse_greenhouse`, `parse_lever`, `parse_ashby`, `parse_smartrecruiters`, `parse_recruitee`, `parse_workable`, `parse_workday`, `parse_phenom`) store the **entire** source JSON object on `Job.raw`:\n\n```python\nout.append(Job(..., raw=j))   # full upstream dict, not just an id\n```\nwhile others (Google, Apple, Meta, Netflix, Microsoft, Amazon) were already trimmed down to `raw={\"id\": ...}` — evidence this was a deliberate optimization applied inconsistently. `raw` is stripped before persisting (`models.py:73 d.pop(\"raw\", None)`), so it's pure in-memory overhead held for the lifetime of the run across potentially thousands of `Job` objects (e.g. Greenhouse/Lever boards can return hundreds of full postings each with descriptions/metadata inline).\n\n**Fix:** trim the remaining full-payload parsers to store only the id fields actually used elsewhere, matching the pattern already used for Google/Apple/Meta/Netflix/Microsoft/Amazon:\n```python\nraw={\"id\": j[\"id\"]},   # instead of raw=j\n```\n\n### Summary (ranked by impact)\n\n| # | Issue | File | Fix effort |\n|---|-------|------|-----------|\n| 1 | N+1 SQLite reads/writes in dedup diff | `store.py:55` | Medium — rewrite `diff()` |\n| 2 | Regex recompiled per job in filter loop | `filters.py:15` | Trivial — hoist `_compile()` out of the loop |\n| 3 | `content_hash` SHA256 computed twice per row | `models.py:66` | Trivial, optional |\n| 4 | No incremental/conditional fetch across scheduled runs | `fetchers.py` (paginated fetchers) | Larger — needs a per-source watermark in `meta` |\n| 5 | Full raw JSON retained on `Job.raw` for 7 of 19 ATS parsers | `fetchers.py` | Trivial — mirror existing trimmed parsers |\n\n#2 is the one I'd fix immediately — zero risk, pure win, and it's the classic \"recompute inside the hot loop\" bug. #1 matters most if `jobs.db` and per-run job volume keep growing (132 sources already, per your recent `feat/microsoft-netflix-amazon` branch).\n",
